<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06324154 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06324154 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  SOMALI; CIVIL; VIOLENCE  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  President Ali Mahdi Mohamed of Somalia was overthrown Monday after two days oftribal fighting between rival forces of the ruling United Somali Congress thatseized power 10 months ago, sources said.;   The sources, who includediplomats and aid workers, quoted Somalia's Radio Mogadishu as saying Gen.Mohamed Farrah Aidid, a clan rival, had toppled Ali Mahdi. They said there hadbeen an undetermined number of casualties and the whereabouts of Ali Mahdiremain unknown.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Front  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  SOMALIA LEADER OUSTED AFTER 10 MONTHS IN POWER  </HEADLINE><TEXT>     The state radio report, monitored in the Somalian capital of Mogadishu byofficials of aid agencies who spoke to their representatives in Nairobi afterhearing the broadcast, could not be confirmed independently.;   Somalia is apoor, mostly Muslim nation of 6 million on the Horn of Africa between the RedSea and Indian Ocean.;   Nearly all telecommunications to Somalia were severedduring street fighting in January that ended President Mohamed Siad Barre's21-year rule. Diplomatic sources say as many as 20,000 people died in thosebattles.;   Since then, Ali Mahdi's government had failed to extend itscontrol beyond the capital, and Somalia's south remained riven by tribalfeuds. The north has been peaceful.;   Sources said fighting broke out Sundayand again Monday morning between forces loyal to Ali Mahdi, 52, and those ofAidid, who is about 60 and is chairman of the ruling party.;   Two sources inNairobi said Aidid and his supporters took over the radio station Monday andthat fighting had subsided by the afternoon.;   During the fighting, theItalian Embassy was destroyed, the sources said. The embassy staff had beengiven protection by Ali Mahdi's forces, the sources said.;   Aidid has accusedthe Italians of being too close to Ali Mahdi and asked them to butt out ofSomali affairs. Only Italy and Egypt had re-established diplomatic missionssince Siad Barre's ouster.;   Ali Mahdi tried to assert his authority inMogadishu on Friday by moving heavy artillery, armored cars and troops intopositions that encroach on territory controlled by Aidid's forces.;  Artillery attacks erupted around Mogadishu, by far Somalia's largest city with1 million residents, until the Muslim combatants broke for tea and prayers inthe late afternoon, the sources said.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  Associated Press  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><CITY>  Nairobi, Kenya  </CITY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   911119  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Tuesday  </DAY><MONTH>  November  </MONTH><PG.COL>  8A  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  362  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Tuesday, November 19, 199100324154,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>